### When should I use this?

You should use this to make fun things! While this post was about parallax, you should take full advantage of your browser‚Äôs 3D features. I‚Äôd love to make a platformer that relies on CSS for many-layered backgrounds, or a solar system you explore via scroll ü§ì

But what if you‚Äôre making a content- or functionality-focused site, not a game or experiment? In this case, I have #complicated #feelings about parallax and other in-your-face animation. I want to create remarkable experiences, I want to change normal modes of engagement and usage, but I also want to make things that are usage and accessible. And this usually means leaving out complex motion such as parallax effects.

As noted on the [WCAG Wiki](https://www.w3.org/WAI/GL/wiki/Animation_caused_by_user_interaction#Description), ‚Äúif scrolling a page causes elements to move (other than the normal movement associated with scrolling) it can trigger vestibular disorders, causing nausea and headaches‚Äù. To comply with the WCAG level A (most-permissive) recommendation, [the user needs a way to turn off those animations](https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG20/#time-limits-pause). While the `prefers-reduced-motion` media query serves this purpose, it is available to a tiny subset of internet users.

Rule of thumb: don‚Äôt use parallax effects outside of an experimental or gaming context. But when you do, have *all* the fun with them. And pure CSS + 3D is far and away the most fun. üòé 

